{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.06,0.21,0.06,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98178"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7660"},{"type":"tags","id":"7871"},{"type":"tags","id":"7872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPure red cell aplasia is a rare condition characterized by severe anaemia and marked reduction or absence of erythroid precursors in the bone marrow, while other cell lines remain normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a cause of pure red cell aplasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myelodysplastic syndrome","Thymoma","Chronic myeloid leukaemia","Multiple myeloma","Aplastic anaemia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPure red cell aplasia (PRCA) is characterized by severe normocytic anaemia, reticulocytopenia, and absence of erythroid precursors in the bone marrow while other cell lines remain normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyelodysplastic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E affects multiple cell lines and shows dysplastic changes across different lineages. \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E affects multiple cell lines with excessive granulocyte production. \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects plasma cells and causes anaemia through bone marrow infiltration. \u003Cstrong\u003EAplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E affects all cell lines and is not specific to red cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ethymoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a well-established cause of PRCA, occurring in about 5-10% of cases. Other important causes include autoimmune conditions, lymphoproliferative disorders, and parvovirus B19 infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pure red cell aplasia is characterized by severe anaemia with isolated erythroid precursor deficiency in the bone marrow","Thymoma is a well-established cause of pure red cell aplasia, occurring in 5-10% of cases","Pure red cell aplasia must be distinguished from conditions affecting multiple cell lines like myelodysplastic syndrome and aplastic anaemia"],"references":["Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone marrow pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Means RT Jr. Pure red cell aplasia. Hematology Am Soc Hematol Educ Program. 2016 Dec 2;2016(1):51-56. doi: 10.1182/asheducation-2016.1.51. PMID: 27913462; PMCID: PMC6142432."]},"re